2. CATCH REGRESSIONS: report any NEW issues the fix introduced (e.g. the fix was incomplete, broke something else, or regressed this dimension), plus any previously-missed real issues.

OUTPUT RULES:
- If a finding is fully resolved, do not re-report it.
- If a finding is only partially addressed or the fix is wrong, report it again (same or new id) with the remaining problem and an updated `fixPrompt`.
- Rate each finding as before: low / medium / high / critical. Findings rated medium or higher will trigger another fixer attempt.
- Set the `dimension` field of your response to exactly "documentation".
- If every previously-reported finding is resolved and the fix introduced no new issues, return applicable=true with an empty findings array.

── PRIOR REVIEW HISTORY for Documentation (initial review + prior review-fixes passes — do NOT re-report resolved findings) ──

### initial review — Reviewed README.md, dev-diary.md, task.md, all XML doc comments on the changed C# surface (FilesController, FileService, IFileService, FileServiceOptions, Models), and JSDoc on the changed/added TypeScript modules (app.ts and the new src/app/* modules, format.ts, router.ts, api.ts, test utilities). Inline API documentation is thorough and matches the implementations; no docstring/code mismatches were found there. The findings are concentrated in README.md and dev-diary.md: the refactor changed two behaviors that the README still describes the old way (home-directory creation is now lazy, not at startup; a new 32-level copy-depth limit was introduced), and two pre-existing completeness gaps (undocumented search-result cap, and the browse response shape omitting two fields) are worth closing alongside them.
- [medium] README claims home folder is created "on startup" but refactor made creation lazy — README.md:36
    The Configuration section states: "The folder is created automatically on startup." This was true before this branch (the old `FileService` constructor called `Directory.CreateDirectory(root)` eagerly), but the refactor in `Services/FileService.cs` now wraps directory creation in a `Lazy<string>` (`_rootLazy`) that is only materialized on first access of the `Root` property — i.e. on the first file-system operation, not at startup/DI resolution. The class XML doc on `FileService` itself was correctly updated ("the directory itself is created lazily on first use"), but the README was not, so a user reading the docs is misled about when (and how late) misconfiguration or disk errors surface. The fix is to update the README sentence to describe lazy creation.
- [medium] Copy depth limit (32) and search result cap (500) are undocumented — README.md
    `Services/FileService.cs` enforces two user-visible limits that the README never mentions. (1) `MaxCopyDepth = 32` is NEW to this branch: `CopyDirectory` aborts with `IOException` ("Directory copy depth limit exceeded (possible cycle)") once recursion reaches 32 levels, so a user copying a deeply nested tree gets an error they cannot explain from the docs. (2) `MaxSearchResults = 500` (pre-existing): `Search` silently stops collecting once it has 500 matches, so a broad query can return fewer results than exist with no indication. Both are behavior-affecting and belong in the README so users understand truncated results / copy failures. Add a short `## Limits` subsection documenting both, including the exact error the copy depth limit raises.
- [low] Verification checklist omits `path` and `parent` from the browse response — README.md:64
    The Final End-to-End Verification Checklist item 5 reads: `GET /api/files/browse?path=` — returns JSON with `entries`, `folderCount`, `fileCount`, and `totalSize`. The actual response (see `Models/FileSystemModels.cs` `BrowseResultDto` and `src/api.ts` `BrowseResult`) also includes `path` (the listed folder's relative path) and `parent` (the normalized parent path, or `null` at the root). A reviewer following the checklist would think two fields are missing when the API is working correctly. Update the checklist to list the full response shape.
- [low] Development diary has no entry for the refactor/hardening work — dev-diary.md
    `dev-diary.md` is the project's development log and currently has only two entries (harness generation; human review with embedded mode). This branch performed substantial additional work — splitting the `src/app.ts` monolith into focused modules under `src/app/`, restructuring the test suite into per-domain files, hardening `FileService` (lazy directory creation, copy-depth guard, idempotent delete, TOCTOU elimination), refactoring `FilesController` with a shared `Execute`/`ExecuteAsync` fault translator, and adding an ESLint flat config — none of which is recorded. The diary should reflect this work so the development history is accurate.

