    The Configuration section states: "The folder is created automatically on startup." This was true before this branch (the old `FileService` constructor called `Directory.CreateDirectory(root)` eagerly), but the refactor in `Services/FileService.cs` now wraps directory creation in a `Lazy<string>` (`_rootLazy`) that is only materialized on first access of the `Root` property — i.e. on the first file-system operation, not at startup/DI resolution. The class XML doc on `FileService` itself was correctly updated ("the directory itself is created lazily on first use"), but the README was not, so a user reading the docs is misled about when (and how late) misconfiguration or disk errors surface. The fix is to update the README sentence to describe lazy creation.
- [medium] Copy depth limit (32) and search result cap (500) are undocumented — README.md
    `Services/FileService.cs` enforces two user-visible limits that the README never mentions. (1) `MaxCopyDepth = 32` is NEW to this branch: `CopyDirectory` aborts with `IOException` ("Directory copy depth limit exceeded (possible cycle)") once recursion reaches 32 levels, so a user copying a deeply nested tree gets an error they cannot explain from the docs. (2) `MaxSearchResults = 500` (pre-existing): `Search` silently stops collecting once it has 500 matches, so a broad query can return fewer results than exist with no indication. Both are behavior-affecting and belong in the README so users understand truncated results / copy failures. Add a short `## Limits` subsection documenting both, including the exact error the copy depth limit raises.
